d=20
> spaces in algebraic topology . Part of this importance is the=20
> difficulty of homotopy theory, which necessitates approximations, and=20
> these are sometimes adequate and convenient.  Henry Whitehead=20
> introduced two methods to approximate homotopy theory: one was to=20
> describe special cases such as the category of polyhedra which were=20
> n-dimensional and r-connected, e.g. n small, or r near to n.=20
or r about half n - cf the stable range
what Schlessinger and I call `shallow'
in rational homotopy theory, still manageable   for r about 1/3 n
> The other was stabilisation. However, in introducing CW-complexes in=20
> ``Combinatorial Homotopy I'' he explains that he does not stick to the=20
> single vertex case since he wants to include covering spaces. There is=20
